Well - this job lasted - until - the first twelve months and then we were put down as what they called - you jumped up in status and - when y
ou come to the - the head - dottler you were - you run into your first years apprenticeship as a placer. See well then you were put down to work with a journeyman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 How old would you be when you became a head dottler?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Fourteen - fifteen. Fourtee
n I think it was. I was fourteen - getting on towards fourteen. But - as things - with me being so quick I jumped me stages. See I could pick things up quickly, I could - I could be in and out the oven quicker than any of the others, even quicker than som
e
 of the journeymen. Well - with me being quick they advanced me - me apprenticeship. Well instead of being in me first year I was put into me third year. Well - by then the first world war had started in 1914. Well I carried on and carried on until - ther
e
 come this - compulsory - conscription, we'd got to come out. Well - bits of - little bits of argument then me papers come through, I'd got to go down to be examined. Well you were paid for that. Your work - no matter how long it took you for go down the 
managers of the works put your money in. Well - I went down and I did't hear no more from mine for, oh - quite a good while. Well I'd worked my way up to the last year of me apprenticeship. That was five years. You had to get five years apprenticeship.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 So it would have been 1916 by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 
Yes. Well in 1916 I joined up. Went and joined the Army. 'Cos we - there was a bit of a dispute on the works so I went and joined up in the Army. I did twelve month - I - I hardly did twelve months - six months in
 England to be correct and I was dispatched overseas. I was - they wanted no one - the Captain and adjutant they wanted to know how - how I'd learnt handle a rifle. Well when they knew as I'd been in the Boys Brigade and knew how to handle a rifle they - 
and knew how to hold a rifle for firing, they were giving me c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14562183\charrsid2163176 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 oss guns and away I went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Where did you go when you went abroad?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 I had go to France. We - we were in France.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Which regiment did you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Across Calais. From Calais to - from Dover to Calais.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Which regiment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Oh I was in the - in the - the Royal Scots Fus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16347937\charrsid2163176 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 liers - when I first joined up. But when we were in France we were transferred from one regiment to another. Finally I found myself in the Royal Fus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16347937\charrsid2163176 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 liers, when I was discharged, I was discharged from the Army in the Royal Fus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16347937\charrsid2163176 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 liers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 How long were you in France before you were wounded?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Well - I was in France twelve months when I first got this - the wound in this leg.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 What happened?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Well, I wasn't long in hospital over that one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 How did you get the wound?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 
Oh well the - it was when we were coming out of the trenches to make another advance on - on the enemy as - I felt - I told you, I felt as though some'at had floated out of the 
fire as you might say and prick your hand, just the same as - a burning - then all of a sudden I felt all me putties as we used to wear then was getting socked up with blood and me leg was beginning to ache. Well when the - the first aid man, the Red Cros
s
 man as was with us noticed it he pulled me down. Well he got killed, when he was doing it. Well in between that I got a back at back - the first bat at back of the neck. Well I happened to recover over this and I - I was sent back again to join what regi
ment I could get - could get into. I happened to join the - the Seaforth Highlanders, 'cos I was happy as a pig - wha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14562183\charrsid2163176 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 
 you call as happy as a pig in muck when I joined them. Well I got in with them 'cos we were in khaki. They took the kilts off 'em, 'cos th
ey couldn't - keep dry. They couldn't keep dry in 'em them kilts, and they were more hindrous. So - the next time I got another wound in the same leg, almost in the same place. That was getting on towards 1918 when I got me - me second bat at the same tim
e, a German must have - I lay there, I could see him coming and I closed my eyes and - I was wounded and instead of him sticking his bayonet in me he give me a clout with the butt of his rifl}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14562183\charrsid2163176 
e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176  - at the back of the head. So - next thing I remembered I was in
 - I was in hospital in - in what they called the casualty clearing station. That was when they were bringing the wounded off the fields and they were put in there before being transferred to other more suitable hospital. Well - from there - I happened to
 
have a - a very faint recollection of where I was and I asked 'em where we were. They said they were in Columbus, in Germany - close to Germany. I said, how're they doing? He said, oh they're doing fine and they're driving them into the sea if they possib
ly can. But next time I started another relapse and - I was down in bottom end of France, right close to the shipping docks, ship - for shipping us out. I was in a nice little hospital, Fr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16064038\charrsid2163176 e}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 nch - amongst a lot of French girls in there - nurses there. Well they got me round a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 And they sent you back to England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 And - Armistice was signed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 You were back in England before the Armistice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 No. I was still in France when the Armistice was signed. Well they put os on - at night time they put
 us on board a shop, were shifting - shifting us across to - to Dover. From Calais to Dover - from Folkestone really I think it was. Some place on the French coast but we - we were moved from there that quickly we hardly realized, but we were put in train
s
 - hospital trains and - I'd only - I was in - they transferred me to - off the train to a hospital in Liverpool. Well - they could do nothing with me there, for my complaints, there was them many they couldn't bed - men were on stretchers, instead of bei
ng in bed they were on stretchers, they hadn't got beds enough. So they asked - they said as they were transferring us across to Birkenhead. That was where I come to be in - this school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 What were they treating you for at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Well - no, they - they managed to get t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16064038\charrsid2163176 he shrapnel - bullet and the sh}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 
rapnel out and they'd healed it up but the - the doctor at the hospital - this hospital in Birkenhead said they'd made a very poor job of it but being as it was a case of emergency it had done a rea
l good job of it but I - you can bend your fingers in it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 So at this time they were treating you for the head injury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Then they were started treating me for this head injury. Well I'd had them many injections round the back of the neck to tr
y to bring me memory back again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 So you lost your memory did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 
Oh I didn't know where the devil I was, no - whether I was in the Army or what the really where I was. Well when I begun get a bit more on me own - on myself same as I was telling
 you, we used to go down, me and a pal of mine used to go down to the Birkenhead docks, fetch these best fruit up in a - in our haversacks, take it back up to the hospital. The - of course when they - when they saw us coming they kno}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16064038\charrsid2163176 wed they was in for a bean of fruit and stuff. Well - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 
one time when I went - the last time I went down really - it was started tumbling down with rain and we hadn't got a big great coats with us and I got soaked straight through to the skin. And I catched me second dose of doubl
e pneumonia. I'd had one dose in France. According to me records.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4598081 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Did they keep you in that same hospital when you got pneumonia?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1265594 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 Yes, they kept }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16064038\charrsid2163176 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 e there until they got me round, got me right. Then they said as they were transferring me to Sheff
ield to a ear hospital as it had affected me ears. With having this butt aback - butt aback of the neck. So while I was in this hospital in - in Sheffield - the word come through, the doctors were thinking about - they said they hadn't got the instruments
 
for do the operation as it was - as it - as it needed. So while I was in there they was giving me treatment, taking me down and giving me treatment for me ears, trying to dry - dry up as much as they possibly could. The - the war finished, peace was signe
d
 - well when peace was signed they said the - they were going to have some consignment had come through for every patient in the hospital was to have a bottle of beer. Well we drank this beer and we had a bit of a celebration, them as could get about, I w
asn't allowed out of bed, but anyway - we had a good time there on this - he said, well}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16064038\charrsid2163176  now, there's the trouble of f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 
ind you an hospital now. This is your time, now, he said, you can get yourself home for good, out of the Army. Well they sent me from there to one hospital, in - just on the out - outside - on the outskirts of Liverpool. Well r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16064038\charrsid2163176 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2966169\charrsid2163176 
om there they despatched me to Clipstone Camp, Military Hospital to - to see what they could do. And they said the best thing as they could do with me was to send me ba
ck home. Give me me - get me discharged. Well I was booked in for me discharge. Well - I said, well -
